.TH SWORDFISH 1 "$(date +"%Y-%m-%d")" "Swordfish 1.2.4" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
swordfish \- A pkill-like CLI tool

.SH SYNOPSIS

 swordfish [-S] [-k] [-K] [-x] [-y] [-p] [-t] [-v] [-h] [-r <time>] [-R] [--sort <ram|age>] [--exclude <pattern>] [--pre-hook <script>] [--post-hook <script>] [--completions <shell> [file]] [--man [file]] [--version] [-u <USER>] pattern...

.SH GENERAL OPTIONS
All flags can be grouped together. For example: "-K -S" can be written as "-KS".
Below are the commonly used options for controlling how Swordfish finds and interacts with processes.

  -h, --help             Show help message
  -v                     Increase verbosity level up to -vvv for maximum verbosity
  -k                     Send SIGTERM to matching processes (graceful shutdown)
  -K                     Send SIGKILL to matching processes (forceful shutdown)
  -S                     Select which processes to act on (interactive prompt)
  -y                     Auto-confirm; skip prompts and confirmation
  -p                     Print raw PIDs only

Supplying a pattern without any signal flags will enter "Static Mode" where Swordfish will
find and display matching processes without sending any signals. Useful for checking
if something is running before you decide to kill it.

By default, Swordfish asks for confirmation before sending signals. Use "-y" to skip
this and execute immediately.

Run 'swordfish --help <category>' for more detail on a specific topic.
.SH SIGNAL CONTROL
Swordfish gives you full control over which signal gets sent to matching processes.

  -k                     Send SIGTERM (graceful shutdown — process can clean up)
  -K                     Send SIGKILL (forceful shutdown — process is terminated immediately)

Think of "-k" as asking nicely and "-K" as not asking at all.

You can also send any arbitrary signal using "-<sig>". Both numeric and named forms work:

  -9                     Send SIGKILL (same as -K)
  -15                    Send SIGTERM (same as -k)
  -10                    Send SIGUSR1
  -TERM                  Send SIGTERM by name
  -KILL                  Send SIGKILL by name
  -HUP                   Send SIGHUP (commonly used to reload configs)

Supported named signals: HUP, INT, QUIT, KILL, TERM, USR1, USR2, STOP, CONT

If you group "-k" and "-K" together (e.g. "-kK"), the last one wins, so "-kK" sends SIGKILL.
.SH FILTERING
By default, Swordfish does a case-insensitive substring match against process names
and command line arguments. The flags below let you narrow down or change how matching works.

  -x                     Exact match only (default: substring match)
  -u <USER>              Only show processes owned by <USER>
  -R                     Hide processes owned by root
  --exclude <pattern>    Exclude processes matching <pattern> from results

Patterns support basic regex. If your pattern looks like a regex (contains ^, $, *, etc.)
Swordfish will compile and use it automatically. Wrap a pattern in ^<pattern>$ to force
an exact match via regex, or just use "-x" for simple exact matching.

Sorting:

  --sort <ram|age>       Sort the process list by RAM usage or age
  ?ram                   Shorthand alias for --sort ram
  ?age                   Shorthand alias for --sort age

The default sort order matches the order entries appear in /proc, which is generally
lowest to highest PID.
.SH BEHAVIOR
When Swordfish matches processes, it shows them and asks for confirmation before
sending any signals. The flags below change how that works.

  -y                     Auto-confirm; skip the confirmation prompt
  -S                     Interactive selection — choose which matched processes to act on
  -t                     Always act on only the top (first) matched process
  -r <time>              Retry every <time> seconds if no processes are matched

Static Mode:
Running Swordfish with just a pattern and no signal flag (no -k, -K, etc.) enters
Static Mode. No signals are sent and just lists matching processes. Good for
checking what's running before committing to a kill.

Verbosity:
The "-v" flag increases how much info is shown per process. Stack up to three:

  0 (default)
    PID "<process>" owned by <user>

  1 (-v)
    PID "<process>" cmdl: "<args>" threads: "<n>" owned by <user>

  2 (-vv)
    [<state>] PID "<process>" cmdl: "<args>" threads: "<n>" owned by <user>

  3 (-vvv)
    [<state>] PID "<process>" cmdl: "<args>" threads: "<n>" owned by <user>
        RAM: "<n> MB" AGE: "<n> min"

Hooks:
Script hooks let you run a file before or after signals are sent. Useful for
notifications, logging, or anything else you want to automate around a kill.

  --pre-hook <script>    Run <script> before sending signals
  --post-hook <script>   Run <script> after sending signals

The script receives the PID and process name as arguments.
.SH MISCELLANEOUS
Shell Completions:
Swordfish officially supports completions for Bash, Zsh, and Fish. Generate them
with "--completions <shell>". Output goes to stdout by default, or to a file if provided.

  --completions <shell> [file]   Generate completions for fish, bash, or zsh

Examples:
  swordfish --completions fish                  Print fish completions to stdout
  swordfish --completions bash ~/.bash_complete Write bash completions to a file

Version:
  --version              Show the current installed version of Swordfish

Man Pages:
Man pages are generated automatically on every build and written to docs/swordfish.1.
You can also generate them manually and write to a custom path:

  --man [file]           Generate the man page, optionally writing to <file>

The man page is built dynamically from all help pages combined and formatted.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
-k firefox
Kill all processes with 'firefox' in the name
.TP
-kx bash
Kill all exact matches of 'bash'
.TP
-Sk KILL vim
Interactively select vim processes and send SIGKILL
.TP
-ky firefox vim bash
Kill all 'firefox', 'vim', and 'bash' processes without confirmation
.TP
-kyr 1 firefox
Recursively kill 'firefox' every 1 second
.TP
--pre-hook script1.sh nvim
Run 'script1.sh' before killing Neovim
.SH SIGNALS
.TP
HUP : Signal number 1
.TP
INT : Signal number 2
.TP
QUIT : Signal number 3
.TP
KILL : Signal number 9
.TP
TERM : Signal number 15
.TP
USR1 : Signal number 10
.TP
USR2 : Signal number 12
.TP
STOP : Signal number 19
.TP
CONT : Signal number 18
